<HEADLINE>
<P>
CURRENT PAPERBACKS: A FATHER'S WORDS BY RICHARD STERN (UNIVERSITY OF CHICAGO 
PRESS: $9.95) 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By CHARLES SOLOMON 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A supposedly comic novel about a divorced father struggling to come to terms 
with his ne'er-do-well son. 
</P>
<P>
Jack, who casually buzzes in and out of jobs and people's lives, obviously is 
intended to exude an irreverent, counterculture charm -- a sort of literary 
equivalent of Michael Parks in "Then Came Bronson." He comes off as a flake, a 
slug and a bore. Cy, the narrator/father, is no prize either, and the two 
characters richly deserve each other. Getting through Stern's wordy prose is as 
cumbersome as chipping through a brick wall with a nut pick, and every bit as 
much fun. 
</P>
</TEXT>
