<HEADLINE>
<P>
GARDEN NEWS; 
</P>
<P>
BLOOD GRASS AVAILABLE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Robert Smaus 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A grass that was rare is becoming more available, now that one of the largest 
wholesale growers, Hines Nurseries, produces it. 
</P>
<P>
Japanese blood grass, Imperata cylindrica 'Rubra,' looks like broken shards of 
stained glass when back lit in the garden. Each blade is green, turning to 
translucent red, and it is most dramatic planted in front of the sun. It 
spreads very slowly in Southern California to make small, 18-inch tall clumps 
and goes completely deciduous in winter. It takes ordinary watering. Robert 
Smaus 
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA041590-0124 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 204714 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
April 15, 1990, Sunday, Home Edition 
