NEW YORK; 
</P>
<P>
5 MILLION CHILDREN BELOW POVERTY LINE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times staff and Wire reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Five million American children under the age of 6 -- almost one out of every 
four in the nation -- recently have been in families living below the poverty 
line, according to a report by the National Center for Children in Poverty, 
which is affiliated with Columbia University in New York. 
</P>
<P>
This makes young children the poorest of any age group in American society, 
with 23% -- more than double the number of adults -- living in poverty, the 
report said. The study, based on 1987 data, found that while 42% of all U.S. 
children living in poverty were white, the percentage of poor among whites 
overall was 13%. That compares to 48% for blacks and 42% for Latinos. 
</P>
</TEXT>
