<HEADLINE>
<P>
POLICE SEEK SUSPECT'S HELP IN FINDING SUBWAY GUNMAN 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By from Newsday 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
NEW YORK 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Detectives searching for the gunman who killed an assailant on a Brooklyn 
subway train sought help Saturday in identifying the shooter from a teen-ager 
charged in the mugging. 
</P>
<P>
Melvin Kirkland, 17, was arrested Friday night after being questioned about the 
shooting, police said. 
</P>
<P>
Kirkland was the first to be arrested from among the group of men who had been 
on a Manhattan-bound express Thursday night when the mugging victim pulled out 
a gun and fired. 
</P>
<P>
Ricky Pickett, 25, the son of a retired bus driver, died from a single shot to 
the heart, police said. Detectives said Kirkland gave them a silver .25-caliber 
semiautomatic handgun, which is believed to be the weapon that was passed among 
the gang on the subway car before the shooting. It was not known whether the 
gun was brandished during the mugging, although police said one of the suspects 
displayed a razor knife. 
</P>
<P>
Sources said detectives had questioned at least two other members of the group. 
Detectives also questioned one passenger who remained on board the train after 
the shooting until police arrived. 
</P>
<P>
Witnesses initially told police Kirkland had fled the train with the gunman's 
wallet, but police said Saturday they were uncertain whether a wallet was taken 
at all. Nor have detectives been able to establish that a watch with a broken 
clasp found inside Pickett's pocket belonged to the gunman. 
</P>
<P>
Kirkland was later charged with second-degree robbery and second-degree assault 
in connection with the attack, police said. 
</P>
<P>
But the public debate that erupted in the aftermath of the shooting continued 
Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
"Two years ago we would have said, 'Turn yourself in,' " said Lisa Sliwa, a 
leader of the Guardian Angels, a civilian anti-crime group. "Now we say: 'Don't 
show your face. If you do, your whole life will be ruined.' " 
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Roy Innis, head of the civil rights group Congress of Racial 
Equality, offered to help the shooter if he decides to come forward. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Wire 
</P>
</TYPE>
