ninth grade. She died of cervical cancer. MICHAEL BURKE / For The Times; Photo, 
Robin Sealander and her boyfriend, Gary Young, in 1987, ; Photo, A PAPNET 
computer selects and displays abnormal cell groups. ; Photo, A doctor uses a 
Cervex-Brush to paint a cell sample on a slide. ; Photo, The nuclei of normal 
cells appear as small, round dots that are uniform in both size and shpe. ; 
Photo, These are cells taken from a post-menopausal patient. Hormonal changes 
may alter cell structure and cause inflammation (the small cells with lobed 
nuclei), but there is no sign of cancer. ; Photo, These cells indicate a 
precancerous condition known as dysplasia., Cell nuclei are enlarged and darker 
than normal, but there is no inflammation. ; Photo, This sample shows cells 
characteristic of an advanced stage of an invasive, malignant cancer. The cell 
nuclei are abnormally large and irregular in shape. Inflammatory cells can also 
be seen. Source: Photographs provided by Dr. William H. Kern, director of the 
Department of Pathology at The Hospital of the Good Samaritan in Los Angeles.; 
