<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE STATE OF THE SPOON 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Barbara Thornburg 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Designers are rethinking the traditional look of knife, fork and spoon. New 
cutlery pieces range from sleekly sculptural to playful: spoons shaped like 
colored fish with checkerboard tails, and knives like sinuously curving bars of 
silver. 
</P>
<P>
High-priced styles are still fashioned of traditional silver and gold, but less 
expensive cutlery is now made of aluminum, brass, wrought iron and plastic. 
</P>
<P>
Many of today's cutlery designers come from a fashion or jewelry background and 
describe their flatware as "functional sculpture." Izabel Lam, who creates 
undulating bronze and silver cutlery, apprenticed with fashion designers 
Geoffrey Beene and Calvin Klein. "A knife and fork must fit snugly into the 
hand. It's just like designing clothes -- they both must fit the moving body," 
she explains. 
</P>
<P>
But what about washing these miniature sculptures? Kirsten Hawthorne, a painter 
and photographer turned flatware artist, swears that her utensils of sterling, 
gold plate and sandblasted plexiglass are dishwasher-safe. But some of these 
avant-garde creations cost up to $110 apiece; it may be prudent to wash this 
new cutlery the old-fashioned way. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, COLOR, New cutlery is made from a variety of materials, from left: 
mother-of-pearl caviar spoon, $34, at Techline Studio/Mix't Collection. 
Stainless-steel-and-acrylic fish-serving spoon by Esotismo, $75 (set of 2), at 
Wilder Place. Kirsten Hawthorne pate server, $110, Aristeia, Brentwood. 
Stainless-and-acrylic fork, $95, at Wilder Place. Horn hors d'oeuvre fork, $10, 
at Deborah Goddard Contemporary Crafts, Santa Monica. Kirsten Hawthorne 
sterling sunflower spoon, $170, Aristeia. Mardi Cohen sterling-silver- 
and-acrylic fork, $180, at Art Options, Santa Monica. ; Photo, COLOR, Sleek 
sculptural shapes include, top from left: Las Culebritas salad spoon by Studio 
Naco, $320 a set, at Gallery of Functional Art, Santa Monica. Gold-and- 
silver-plated cutlery by Tsuki, $210 to $275 for a three-piece setting, and 
Quest stainless-steel fork by Yamazaki, $34 for a five-piece setting, at Steve, 
Beverly Hills. Izabel Lam bronze spoon, $155 for a five-piece place setting, at 
Tesoro. ; Photo, COLOR, Gold-and-silver-plated knife by Tsuki, bottom 
(upright), $275 for a three-piece setting, at Steve. Bissell &amp; Wilhite Xum 
stainless knife, $75 for a five-piece setting, at Art Options, Santa Monica. ; 
Photo, COLOR, Kirsten Hawthorne's distinctly sculptural sandblasted-plexiglass 
salad servers, right, are dishwasher safe; $195 for the large set, $185 for the 
small set, at Steve. Arthead 
</P>
